      <h2>The Trap Most Men Over 40 Fall Into</h2>

      <p>
        Here's the pattern. A man over 40 decides to lose 20 pounds. He cuts calories — eats less, skips snacks, maybe cuts carbs. He loses weight. Then something goes wrong that he can't quite explain.
      </p>

      <p>
        He feels weaker. His metabolism seems slower. The weight comes back faster than it came off. He looks smaller but not leaner. Six months later he weighs roughly what he did before, but his body composition is actually worse — less muscle, more fat — than when he started.
      </p>

      <div class="fix-grid">
        <div class="fix-card problem">
          <div class="fc-label">✗ What happened</div>
          <div class="fc-text">He lost weight — but a significant portion of that weight was muscle, not fat. His body, in a calorie deficit without enough protein, broke down muscle tissue for energy.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="fix-card solution">
          <div class="fc-label">✓ What prevents it</div>
          <div class="fc-text">High protein intake during a deficit signals the body to preserve muscle and burn fat instead. The deficit stays, but the composition of what you lose changes entirely.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="fix-card problem">
          <div class="fc-label">✗ The downstream effect</div>
          <div class="fc-text">Less muscle means a slower resting metabolism. The body now burns fewer calories at rest — making it progressively harder to lose weight and easier to regain it.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="fix-card solution">
          <div class="fc-label">✓ The better outcome</div>
          <div class="fc-text">Preserved muscle keeps metabolism elevated. Weight loss is sustainable. The body you end up with after the cut is stronger, not just lighter.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        This isn't a discipline failure. It's a protein failure. And it's dramatically worse after 40 because of <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/anabolic-resistance-after-40/">anabolic resistance</a> — the biological mechanism that makes aging muscle less efficient at using dietary protein. You need more protein to get the same protective effect, not less.
      </p>

      <div class="link-box">
        <strong>The biology behind this</strong>
        <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/sarcopenia-men-over-40/">Sarcopenia — why men over 40 lose muscle faster than they realize, and what stops it →</a>
      </div>

      <h2>Why Your Protein Target Goes Up When You're Cutting</h2>

      <p>
        During normal eating — maintenance calories — the research-backed protein target for men over 40 is around 1.2g per kilogram of bodyweight per day. That's what it takes to maintain muscle against the effects of <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/anabolic-resistance-after-40/">anabolic resistance</a> and age-related muscle loss.
      </p>

      <p>
        During a calorie deficit, that target rises to <strong>1.6g/kg</strong>. The reason is straightforward: when calories are restricted, the body is under pressure to find energy from somewhere. More dietary protein makes muscle a less attractive target. It's the difference between your body burning fat for fuel and burning your hard-earned muscle instead.
      </p>

      <!-- TARGET CARDS -->
      <div class="target-grid">
        <div class="target-card">
          <div class="tc-label">Maintenance target</div>
          <div class="tc-number">1.2g/kg</div>
          <div class="tc-desc">Preserves muscle at normal calorie intake. The baseline for men over 40 not in a deficit.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="target-card">
          <div class="tc-label">Weight loss target</div>
          <div class="tc-number">1.6g/kg</div>
          <div class="tc-desc">Protects muscle during a calorie deficit. Higher requirement, not lower. Most men get this backwards.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        Most men do the opposite. They cut calories and protein simultaneously — smaller portions across the board. That's the formula for losing muscle. The right formula is to cut calories while holding or increasing protein, which forces the deficit to come from fat stores instead of muscle tissue.
      </p>

      <div class="pull-quote">
        <p>"Cut calories. Hold protein. That's the whole strategy. Everything else is secondary."</p>
      </div>

