      <h2>Three Reasons High Protein Accelerates Fat Loss</h2>

      <p>
        Muscle preservation is the primary reason — but it's not the only one. High protein intake during a deficit works on multiple levels simultaneously.
      </p>

      <!-- COMPARE TABLE -->
      <div class="compare-table-wrap">
        <table class="compare-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Mechanism</th>
              <th>What it means</th>
              <th>Impact on fat loss</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Muscle preservation</strong></td>
              <td>Protein signals the body to burn fat, not muscle, in a deficit</td>
              <td class="good">Keeps metabolism from slowing</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Thermic effect</strong></td>
              <td>20–35% of protein calories are burned in digestion — highest of any macro</td>
              <td class="good">Burns more calories from the same food</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Satiety</strong></td>
              <td>Protein reduces hunger hormones (ghrelin) and increases fullness hormones</td>
              <td class="good">Easier to maintain the deficit</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Low protein approach</strong></td>
              <td>Body loses muscle alongside fat, metabolism slows</td>
              <td class="bad">Weight comes back faster</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
