      <p>
        The thermic effect alone is worth understanding. Fat and carbohydrates burn 3–8% of their calories in digestion. Protein burns 20–35%. That means a 500-calorie protein serving effectively costs closer to 325–400 net calories. You're getting a built-in calorie discount on the one macro that also protects your muscle. Nothing else on the nutrition side of weight loss comes close to that return.
      </p>

      <h2>The Right Way to Structure a Deficit After 40</h2>

      <p>
        This isn't complicated, but the sequencing matters. Most men approach it backwards.
      </p>

      <div class="callout">
        <p><strong>Step 1:</strong> Set your protein target first — 1.6g/kg of bodyweight per day. This is non-negotiable during a cut.<br><br>
        <strong>Step 2:</strong> Create a moderate calorie deficit (300–500 calories below maintenance). Not aggressive — sustainable.<br><br>
        <strong>Step 3:</strong> Let the deficit come from reducing fat and carbohydrates, not protein. Protein stays high regardless of what else changes.<br><br>
        <strong>Step 4:</strong> Add or maintain resistance training. Muscle under load is muscle that stays. Training is the signal; protein is the raw material.</p>
      </div>

      <p>
        The men who lose fat and keep muscle after 40 aren't doing anything exotic. They're running a moderate deficit with high protein and some form of resistance training. That's the entire framework. The problem is most weight loss advice hands them a calorie number and sends them on their way — with no guidance on where that deficit should come from.
      </p>

      <h2>What This Means for Tracking</h2>

      <p>
        If you're in a deficit, the stakes for hitting your protein target are higher than at maintenance. Missing by 30g when you're trying to lose weight isn't just leaving muscle-building on the table — it's actively risking the muscle you already have.
      </p>

      <p>
        This is exactly why visibility matters. <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/hard-to-hit-protein-goal-after-40/">Hitting 120g+ every day is already hard after 40</a> — hitting 130–150g while eating fewer total calories is harder. You need to know where you stand at lunch, not at dinner when it's too late to course-correct.
      </p>

      <p>
        One number. Tracked simply. Checked mid-day. That's the feedback loop that makes the difference between a cut that works and one that costs you muscle you'll spend years trying to rebuild.
      </p>

