        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How much protein should men over 40 eat to lose weight?</h3>
          <p>Men over 40 trying to lose weight should target 1.6g of protein per kilogram of bodyweight per day — higher than the 1.2g/kg maintenance target. At this level, protein protects muscle mass during a calorie deficit, keeping metabolism from slowing and ensuring the weight lost is fat, not muscle.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Why do men over 40 lose muscle when they diet?</h3>
          <p>When men over 40 cut calories without increasing protein, the body turns to muscle tissue for energy. This is accelerated by anabolic resistance — the reduced ability of aging muscle to use dietary protein efficiently. The result is weight loss that includes significant muscle loss, which slows metabolism and makes weight regain more likely.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Does eating more protein help with weight loss after 40?</h3>
          <p>Yes — in multiple ways. High protein intake during weight loss preserves muscle mass, which keeps metabolism elevated. Protein also has the highest thermic effect of any macronutrient (20–35% of calories burned in digestion), reduces hunger, and increases satiety. Men who maintain high protein during a deficit lose more fat and less muscle than those who don't.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Can you lose fat and keep muscle after 40?</h3>
          <p>Yes — but only if protein intake is high enough during the deficit. The combination of 1.6g/kg of protein per day, a moderate calorie deficit, and resistance training is what allows men over 40 to lose fat while maintaining muscle. The key is that protein target goes up, not down, when cutting.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What happens to metabolism when men over 40 diet without enough protein?</h3>
          <p>Without adequate protein during a calorie deficit, the body loses muscle alongside fat. Muscle burns calories at rest — less of it means a slower resting metabolism. This makes it progressively harder to lose weight and easier to regain it. It's the cycle most men over 40 experience when they diet without a protein focus.</p>
        </div>

